        "text": "This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nSummary:\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   The user provided issue #30 (https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/issues/30) titled \"[A3] Trace mode for evaluation\" to solve. Specific requirements:\n   - Add `--trace` flag to both `js/` and `rust/` CLI runners\n   - Add library-level option `trace: true`\n   - Print every reduction step, operator resolution, and assignment lookup with span info\n   - Format like `[span demo.lino:3:1] resolve (and: avg)` and `[span demo.lino:5:1] eval (a = a) → assigned 1`\n   - Trace output must be reproducible (no nondeterminism)\n   - Tests verify trace lines for representative programs\n   - Documented in `docs/DIAGNOSTICS.md`\n   - Update existing PR #101 (currently draft/WIP) on branch `issue-30-fbacf7f8954b`\n   - Working directory: `/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370`\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - Relative Meta-Logic (RML) over LiNo (Links Notation)\n   - Many-valued logic (binary, ternary, fuzzy, probabilistic)\n   - Two parallel implementations: JavaScript (js/src/rml-links.mjs) and Rust (rust/src/lib.rs)\n   - Structured Diagnostics with error codes (E001-E006), spans (file/line/col/length)\n   - AST evaluation with operator resolution (and, or, not, =, !=, both, neither)\n   - Probability assignments via `((expr) has probability p)`\n   - Operator redefinition via `(name: ...)` form\n   - LiNo parser via `links-notation` package\n   - Top-level form span tracking via `computeFormSpans()` / `compute_form_spans()`\n   - Panic-to-Diagnostic conversion in Rust (decode_panic_payload)\n\n3. Files and Code Sections:\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/js/src/rml-links.mjs** (modified)\n     - Main JS evaluator. Added TraceEvent class, formatTraceEvent function, formatTraceValue helper, _tracer/_currentSpan on Env, trace() method, hooked trace events into operator definitions, equality lookups, probability assignments, and top-level form evaluation. Updated CLI to parse `--trace` flag. Fixed `computeFormSpans` to handle inline comments after `)` so depth counter doesn't get confused by parens inside comments. Added exports: `TraceEvent`, `formatTraceEvent`.\n     - Key code added:\n     ```js\n     class TraceEvent {\n       constructor({ kind, detail, span }) {\n         this.kind = kind;\n         this.detail = detail;\n         this.span = span || { file: null, line: 1, col: 1, length: 0 };\n       }\n     }\n     function formatTraceEvent(event) {\n       const span = event.span || { file: null, line: 1, col: 1, length: 0 };\n       const file = span.file || '<input>';\n       return `[span ${file}:${span.line}:${span.col}] ${event.kind} ${event.detail}`;\n     }\n     // Env: this._tracer = null; this._currentSpan = null;\n     // Env method: trace(kind, detail){ if (this._tracer) this._tracer(kind, detail, this._currentSpan); }\n     ```\n     - In `evaluate()`:\n     ```js\n     const traceEnabled = !!opts.trace;\n     const trace = traceEnabled ? [] : null;\n     if (traceEnabled) {\n       env._tracer = (kind, detail, span) => {\n         trace.push(new TraceEvent({ kind, detail, span: span || { file, line: 1, col: 1, length: 0 } }));\n       };\n     }\n     // For each form: env._currentSpan = span; ... emit 'eval' event with key + result summary\n     ```\n     - CLI updated to parse `--trace` flag and write trace events to stderr via `console.error(formatTraceEvent(event))`.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/rust/src/lib.rs** (NOT YET modified)\n     - Rust mirror needs equivalent changes: TraceEvent struct, evaluate() trace option, hooks at apply_eq, define_form (operator redef), assignment in eval_node, top-level form eval.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/rust/src/main.rs** (NOT YET modified)\n     - CLI needs `--trace` flag added.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/docs/DIAGNOSTICS.md** (NOT YET modified)\n     - Needs Trace section.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/js/tests/diagnostics.test.mjs** (existing reference)\n     - Pattern for new trace tests in JS.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/rust/tests/diagnostics_tests.rs** (existing reference)\n     - Pattern for mirrored Rust trace tests.\n\n   - **/tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/examples/demo.lino** (used for testing)\n     - 15-line file used to verify trace output.\n\n4. Errors and fixes:\n   - **`Cannot find package 'links-notation'`**: Fixed by running `npm install` in `js/` directory.\n   - **Wrong span for `(or: max)` (showed line 6:21 instead of 7:1)**: The existing `computeFormSpans` didn't handle inline comments after `)` followed by whitespace, so parens inside `# so (1 and 0) = 0.5` corrupted depth tracking. Fixed by adding tracking of `lastClosingDepthZeroCol` and `sawWsAfterClose` state to detect `)\\s+#...` inline comments and skip them.\n\n5. Problem Solving:\n   - Designed unified trace event format `[span <file>:<line>:<col>] <kind> <details>` matching the issue's example output.\n   - Identified four trace event kinds: `resolve` (operator definition/redefinition), `assign` (probability assignment), `lookup` (assignment lookup at `=`), `eval` (top-level form reduction).\n   - Made trace deterministic by using fixed top-level form iteration and recursion order; verified by diffing two consecutive runs.\n   - Used Env-level `_currentSpan` field set per top-level form so leaf hooks can attach a location without threading spans through every helper.\n   - All 424 existing JS tests still pass after changes.\n\n6. All user messages:\n   - **Initial task**: \"Issue to solve: https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/issues/30 / Your prepared branch: issue-30-fbacf7f8954b / Your prepared working directory: /tmp/gh-issue-solver-1777477820370 / Your prepared Pull Request: https://github.com/link-foundation/relative-meta-logic/pull/101 / Proceed.\"\n   - **Tool loaded confirmation** (after ToolSearch): \"Tool loaded.\"\n   - **System reminders** (multiple): About task tools, deferred tools, available skills, user context.\n   - **Final message**: Request for a detailed summary in <analysis> and <summary> tags, no tool calls.\n\n7. Pending Tasks:\n   - **Task #4 (in progress)**: Implement `--trace` flag in Rust runner — mirror JS trace output for parity.\n   - **Task #5**: Add JS and Rust trace tests (representative programs).\n   - **Task #6**: Document trace mode in `docs/DIAGNOSTICS.md`.\n   - **Task #7**: Update PR #101 description and mark ready-for-review (`gh pr edit`, `gh pr ready 101`).\n   - Also: Commit changes to branch `issue-30-fbacf7f8954b`, push to remote.\n\n8. Current Work:\n   Immediately before the summary request, I had completed the JS implementation of trace mode. All 424 JS tests pass. I verified determinism by comparing two trace outputs. I had just marked Task #3 as completed and Task #4 as in_progress to begin the Rust implementation. The plan was to mirror the JS implementation in Rust by:\n   - Adding a `TraceEvent` struct and `format_trace_event` function in `rust/src/lib.rs`\n   - Adding tracer/current_span fields to `Env` struct\n   - Adding hooks at `apply_eq` (lookup events), `define_form` (resolve events for operator redefinition/aggregator selection), assignment branch in `eval_node` (assign events), and `evaluate()` (eval events per top-level form)\n   - Adding a trace option to `evaluate()` (likely via expanded `EnvOptions` or a new options struct)\n   - Adding `--trace` flag parsing to `rust/src/main.rs`\n   - Then mirroring the span fix from JS in `compute_form_spans`\n\n9. Optional Next Step:\n   Continue with Task #4: Implement `--trace` flag in Rust runner. The task description from TaskCreate was: \"Mirror JS trace output for parity\". I had just set this task to in_progress with `TaskUpdate({ taskId: '4', status: 'in_progress' })` and was about to read/edit `rust/src/lib.rs` and `rust/src/main.rs` to add equivalent trace functionality matching the JS implementation. The Rust implementation must produce identical trace output format `[span <file>:<line>:<col>] <kind> <details>` with the same kinds (resolve, assign, lookup, eval) so cross-runtime drift fails CI tests, consistent with how diagnostics are kept in lock-step between the two implementations.\n\nIf you need specific details from before compaction (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /home/box/.claude/projects/-tmp-gh-issue-solver-1777477820370/28a784f8-3dce-46c6-bfe0-3826da2572a7.jsonl\nContinue the conversation from where it left off without asking the user any further questions. Resume directly — do not acknowledge the summary, do not recap what was happening, do not preface with \"I'll continue\" or similar. Pick up the last task as if the break never happened."
